:R-HSA-71288  a             obo:GO_0006600 , owl:NamedIndividual ;
        rdfs:comment        "In humans, creatine is synthesized primarily in the liver and kidney, from glycine, arginine, and S-adenosylmethionine, in a sequence of two reactions. From the liver, creatine is exported to tissues such as skeletal muscle and brain, where it undergoes phosphorylation and serves as a short-term energy store. The mechanism by which creatine leaves producer tissues is unclear, but its uptake by consumer tissues is mediated by the SLC6A8 transporter.<P>Once formed, phosphocreatine undergoes a slow spontaneous reaction to form creatinine, which is excreted from the body." ;
        rdfs:label          "Creatine metabolism" ;
        dc:contributor      "Edited: D'Eustachio, P, 0000-00-00 00:00:00" , "GOC:reactome_curators" , "Authored: 2003-04-23 00:00:00" ;
        dc:date             "2026-06-29" ;
        pav:providedBy      "https://reactome.org" ;
        oboInOwl:hasDbXref  "R-HSA-71288" ;
        skos:narrower       <http://model.geneontology.org/R-HSA-71291/R-HSA-71291> ;
        skos:note           "org.biopax.paxtools.model.level3.Pathway" .

